{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture early programmers as chefs with one giant pot: every ingredient dumped in, everything stirred together. It worked—until the recipe got big, and one tiny change spoiled the whole batch.",
      "title": "When code was one big soup"
    },
    {
      "text": "As programs grew, teams tripped over each other. Fixing a bug felt like pulling a loose thread and watching a sweater unravel. People needed a way to tame complexity without slowing down.",
      "title": "The chaos of growing software"
    },
    {
      "text": "The first fix was “break it into functions.” Like cutting a song into verses and choruses, it added structure. But the data still wandered around, touched by anything, anywhere—easy to misuse.",
      "title": "Functions helped… but not enough"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came a bold idea: bundle data with the code that uses it, like a game character carrying its own stats and moves. Now behavior lived next to what it affected, instead of across the map.",
      "title": "A new idea: data with behavior"
    },
    {
      "text": "Objects became little self-contained “machines.” You push buttons (methods), you don’t fiddle with the gears inside (encapsulation). Suddenly, changes could stay local instead of rippling everywhere.",
      "title": "Encapsulation: hiding the gears"
    },
    {
      "text": "Developers also wanted reuse without copy-paste. Inheritance offered a family tree: make a “Vehicle,” then “Car” and “Bike.” It was powerful—sometimes messy—but it changed how people organized code.",
      "title": "Inheritance: the family tree trick"
    },
    {
      "text": "Polymorphism added a magic remote: different devices, same buttons. Call “draw” or “play,” and each object responds in its own way. Programs became more flexible, like swapping LEGO pieces mid-build.",
      "title": "Polymorphism: same call, new result"
    },
    {
      "text": "Why does OOP still matter? Because modern apps are crowded cities—features, teams, deadlines. OOP gives you zoning laws: clear boundaries, reusable parts, and safer change—so software can grow without collapsing.",
      "title": "Why it changed everything"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture ancient engineers measuring land and building temples. Geometry worked great for still shapes—triangles, circles, clean edges. But the moment things moved, math started to feel like a frozen photograph.",
      "title": "Math in a world that stood still"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now imagine chasing a speeding arrow. You can measure where it was, and where it ends up—but what about its speed at one instant? Like trying to judge a song’s tempo from two notes, the “in-between” was missing.",
      "title": "The mystery of “right now”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Astronomers watched planets wander across the sky like stubborn dancers. Predicting tomorrow’s position meant understanding motion itself, not just snapshots. Old tools could estimate, but they couldn’t pin down change cleanly.",
      "title": "Planets didn’t follow straight lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "People tried clever hacks: smaller and smaller time steps, thinner and thinner slices. It was like cutting a loaf of bread into ever-finer pieces to guess its curve. Useful—but always felt like approximation, not truth.",
      "title": "Slicing the problem to death"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came a daring idea: what if you could talk about change by letting a step size shrink toward zero—without needing it to be zero? A kind of mathematical zoom lens that reveals what happens at the sharpest scale.",
      "title": "A zoom lens called “approaching zero”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Two minds chased it from different angles. Newton wanted the math of motion and gravity; Leibniz wanted a crisp language for curves. They met in the same place: a toolkit for change, written in symbols that stuck.",
      "title": "Newton and Leibniz, same itch"
    },
    {
      "text": "One half of the new toolkit measured instant change—like reading a car’s speedometer instead of averaging a trip. The other half added up tiny pieces—like counting drops to know the volume of a bucket.",
      "title": "Speedometers and buckets"
    },
    {
      "text": "The shocker was that these two ideas—measuring change and adding slices—fit together like a lock and key. What looked like separate puzzles snapped into one story about how nature moves and how quantities accumulate.",
      "title": "Two puzzles click into one"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, calculus is the behind-the-scenes engine in science, engineering, and data: from designing bridges to training AI, from modeling epidemics to pricing loans. It’s how we turn “it’s changing” into something we can compute.",
      "title": "Why it still runs the modern world"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "For most of human history, species felt like furniture: lions were lions, oaks were oaks—fixed pieces in nature’s living room. If something changed, it seemed like a mistake or a mystery, not a rule.",
      "title": "A World of Unchanging Creatures"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then explorers started bringing home “weird cousins” of familiar animals. Why would islands have birds that look almost the same—but with different beaks, colors, and habits? Nature was hinting at a bigger story.",
      "title": "Clues Arrive in Crates"
    },
    {
      "text": "People had explanations, but they fought each other. Some said species were designed as-is. Others whispered that life might shift over time. The problem: nobody had a simple, believable engine to drive change.",
      "title": "The Missing Mechanism"
    },
    {
      "text": "In 1831, a young Charles Darwin stepped onto the HMS Beagle. Think of it like a five-year road trip with a notebook—storms, fossils, mountains, and endless specimens—each stop adding pressure to old ideas.",
      "title": "A Notebook on a Long Voyage"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fossils looked like ghosts of modern animals—similar, but not identical. Why would a giant extinct “armadillo” look like today’s armadillo? It was as if the past was remixing the present.",
      "title": "Fossils That Felt Like Family"
    },
    {
      "text": "On the Galápagos, tiny differences shouted loud. Finches had beaks like specialized tools: pliers, tweezers, nutcrackers. Same basic bird, different jobs. The islands felt like separate test kitchens for life.",
      "title": "The Islands’ Living Workshop"
    },
    {
      "text": "Back home, Darwin saw a clue in plain sight: breeders. Pigeons, dogs, crops—people could sculpt traits by choosing who reproduces. If humans could “select,” what if nature was doing it nonstop?",
      "title": "Aha: Nature as a Breeder"
    },
    {
      "text": "The big squeeze was survival. More offspring are born than can possibly live—like too many tickets for too few seats. Small advantages matter, and over many generations, those advantages can reshape a whole lineage.",
      "title": "The Struggle Behind the Scenes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Darwin’s idea clicked into place: natural selection. Not a ladder aiming for “better,” but a filter—traits that fit today’s environment tend to stick around. Change the environment, and the filter changes too.",
      "title": "Natural Selection: The Filter"
    },
    {
      "text": "When Darwin published, it landed like thunder. It offered a unifying story for biodiversity—why there are so many forms of life, why they fit their habitats, and why they share deep similarities.",
      "title": "A Storm of a Book"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, evolution isn’t just a history lesson. It helps explain antibiotic resistance, emerging viruses, conservation decisions, and even why your own body has ancient quirks. It’s the thread that ties biology together.",
      "title": "Why It Still Matters Now"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture strangers in a busy marketplace arguing about justice, gods, and taxes. Voices rise, confidence is loud—and yet nobody can tell whose reasons actually hold up. Winning sounds a lot like being louder.",
      "title": "When arguing was just noise"
    },
    {
      "text": "People leaned on tradition, authority, or gut feeling—like navigating a storm by vibes. Sometimes it worked. Often it didn’t. The real problem: even smart people could talk themselves into nonsense.",
      "title": "Smart minds, shaky conclusions"
    },
    {
      "text": "So thinkers started hunting for something steadier: rules that don’t change with mood, status, or crowd approval. Like wanting a reliable recipe instead of guessing spices every time.",
      "title": "The craving for a “recipe”"
    },
    {
      "text": "In ancient Greece, the spotlight turned to how we reason. If two claims clash, what decides the winner—power or proof? The big idea: arguments can be tested, not just performed.",
      "title": "A new focus: proof over power"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aristotle treats thinking like craftwork. He looks for the “joinery” of arguments—the patterns that make conclusions click into place when the pieces fit, and fall apart when they don’t.",
      "title": "Aristotle’s blueprint for thought"
    },
    {
      "text": "Logic became a kind of mental referee: it doesn’t tell you what to believe, but it checks whether your beliefs play fair. Like rules of a game that keep skill from turning into chaos.",
      "title": "A referee for ideas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, logic is the quiet backbone of debates, science, law, and everyday decisions. In a world full of confident claims, it’s your flashlight—helping you see which paths are solid and which are traps.",
      "title": "Why it still matters now"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagina ir à feira com a mesma nota de sempre e voltar com sacolas mais leves. Nada “místico” aconteceu: o dinheiro não mudou de cor — mudou de força. Essa sensação de que a nota encolheu é o ponto de partida da inflação.",
      "title": "Quando a nota “encolhe”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Antes de existir índice e gráfico, as pessoas já notavam: o pão ficava menor, o aluguel apertava, a passagem subia. Era como tentar correr numa esteira que acelera sem avisar — você se esforça, mas parece ficar no mesmo lugar.",
      "title": "A vida antes do termômetro"
    },
    {
      "text": "O problema é que preços não sobem por esporte. Quando muita gente quer comprar e não tem produto suficiente, o preço vira leilão. Quando produzir fica mais caro, o preço vira repasse. Inflação é essa pressão no placar.",
      "title": "Por que os preços puxam para cima"
    },
    {
      "text": "No começo, tentavam “resolver no grito”: congelar preços, culpar comerciantes, trocar moeda. Às vezes dá alívio rápido, como colocar fita num cano furado. Mas se a água continua pressionando, o vazamento volta em outro lugar.",
      "title": "Remédios que só disfarçam"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com o tempo, veio o insight: medir ajuda a discutir. Nasceram índices de preços, uma espécie de “cesta de compras padrão”. Eles não contam uma história perfeita, mas dão um mapa: onde está ficando mais caro e com que velocidade.",
      "title": "A descoberta de medir a cesta"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inflação mexe com tudo: salário, poupança, dívidas, contratos. Para quem recebe depois, é como chegar atrasado ao buffet: os preços já mudaram. Para quem reajusta antes, pode ser escudo. Ela redistribui sem pedir licença.",
      "title": "Quem perde, quem ganha, quem aperta"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hoje, entender inflação é entender seu cotidiano. Ela está no reajuste do aluguel, no mercado do mês, no juros do cartão. É o “clima” dos preços: não dá pra controlar com vontade, mas dá pra se preparar quando você sabe ler o céu.",
      "title": "Por que isso importa agora"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagina una manzana cayendo y, muy arriba, la Luna “sin caerse”. Por siglos, eso parecía dos historias distintas: una para la Tierra y otra para el cielo. La gravedad nace cuando alguien se atreve a decir: tal vez es la misma fuerza.",
      "title": "Dos mundos que no se tocaban"
    },
    {
      "text": "En la vida diaria bastaba con decir “las cosas pesadas caen”. Pero esa idea era como una receta sin medidas: no predecía nada. ¿Por qué cae una piedra y una pluma flota? ¿Y por qué los planetas no se apagan como trompos?",
      "title": "El misterio de lo “natural”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aristóteles imaginó que todo buscaba su “lugar”: la piedra hacia abajo, el fuego hacia arriba. Sonaba ordenado, como un mapa viejo con bordes bonitos… pero el cielo no obedecía igual. Los planetas hacían bucles extraños en el firmamento.",
      "title": "Un mapa bonito, pero incompleto"
    },
    {
      "text": "Para salvar ese cielo caprichoso, se inventaron engranajes invisibles: círculos sobre círculos, como una bicicleta con mil cadenas. Funcionaba a ratos, pero era un parche. Cada nueva observación pedía otro círculo más. El sistema crujía.",
      "title": "El cielo con “rueditas”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Luego llegó Galileo, mirando caer cosas de verdad. Descubrió que el movimiento tiene terquedad: un objeto quiere seguir como va si nada lo frena. Fue como entender que una pelota en hielo no “necesita” empuje constante… solo necesita que no la detengan.",
      "title": "Galileo y la terquedad del movimiento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Kepler, con los datos de Tycho, encontró la melodía escondida: los planetas no van en círculos perfectos, sino en elipses, y corren más cuando están cerca del Sol. Era música matemática. Faltaba el instrumento que la tocara: la causa.",
      "title": "Kepler escucha la órbita"
    },
    {
      "text": "Newton juntó piezas como un chef que por fin entiende el sabor: si la Luna cae siempre, pero también avanza, nunca llega al suelo; se queda orbitando. La caída y la órbita eran el mismo plato, servido a distinta velocidad.",
      "title": "La caída que se vuelve órbita"
    },
    {
      "text": "Con una sola regla, Newton conectó la manzana con Júpiter: una atracción que crece con la masa y se debilita con la distancia. De pronto podías predecir eclipses, mareas y trayectorias, como si el universo fuese un reloj… pero uno que puedes calcular.",
      "title": "Una ley para la Tierra y el cielo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hoy la gravedad sigue guiando satélites, GPS y viajes espaciales. También nos recuerda algo hermoso: las mismas reglas que te pegan al piso dibujan las rutas de los planetas. Entenderla es como leer el “manual” del cosmos en voz alta.",
      "title": "Por qué importa hoy"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture an old chatbot like a wind-up toy: you pulled a string (typed a question) and it rattled off a prewritten line. If you phrased it “wrong,” it stalled. Early language AI lived and died by exact wording.",
      "title": "When chatbots were wind-up toys"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rule-based systems tried to bottle language like a recipe: “IF you see X, say Y.” But human speech is jazz—slang, sarcasm, typos, context. The rulebooks grew into tangled vines, and still missed the point.",
      "title": "The rulebook that couldn’t fit"
    },
    {
      "text": "So researchers changed tactics: stop hard-coding answers; start learning from examples. Like a kid picking up a language by hearing it everywhere, models began to study huge piles of text and notice patterns humans never wrote down.",
      "title": "Learning beats lecturing"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came a key idea: attention. Instead of reading a sentence like a train on fixed tracks, models could glance around the whole line—like highlighting the important words while you read—linking “it” to what “it” refers to.",
      "title": "Attention: the highlighter moment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Scale turned the dial to eleven. With more data, bigger models, and faster chips, the same basic approach went from “pretty good autocomplete” to “wait… it explains, summarizes, translates, and chats?”",
      "title": "When scale changed the vibe"
    },
    {
      "text": "These models became large language models: not a list of rules, but a dense map of how words tend to work together. Like a seasoned traveler, they’ve seen so many conversations that they can guess what comes next in new ones.",
      "title": "LLMs: a map of language"
    },
    {
      "text": "Why it matters now: language is the interface to everything—search, support, coding, learning. LLMs moved AI from button-press tools to conversation partners, raising big questions about accuracy, bias, and trust.",
      "title": "Why you’re hearing about them everywhere"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine doing math like organizing a messy garage: piles everywhere, labels missing, and you keep arguing whether two piles are “the same.” For centuries, mathematicians used collections constantly—but mostly by gut feel.",
      "title": "Before sets had a name"
    },
    {
      "text": "Numbers, shapes, solutions to equations—people kept grouping things. But without rules, “collection” was a vague word, like saying “a bunch of songs” without agreeing what counts as a song.",
      "title": "The irresistible urge to group"
    },
    {
      "text": "As math grew, the piles got weird: all triangles, all functions, all infinite decimals. Infinity isn’t a bigger box—it’s a different game. Old intuition started slipping like shoes on ice.",
      "title": "Then infinity crashed the party"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the late 1800s, Georg Cantor dared to compare infinities. Some infinite sets were “bigger” than others. It was like discovering not all oceans hold the same amount of water.",
      "title": "Cantor’s bold new lens"
    },
    {
      "text": "But the freedom came with a price: if you let “any definable collection” count, you can build monsters. Think of a rulebook that allows a move that breaks the whole game.",
      "title": "When “anything goes” breaks"
    },
    {
      "text": "Russell exposed the crack with a simple trap: the set of all sets that don’t contain themselves. If it contains itself, it shouldn’t; if it doesn’t, it should. A logic Möbius strip.",
      "title": "Russell’s paradox bomb"
    },
    {
      "text": "So mathematicians tightened the bolts. They built axioms—careful rules for forming sets—like a kitchen safety code: you can cook almost anything, but not in ways that burn the house down.",
      "title": "Axioms: the safety rails"
    },
    {
      "text": "With that foundation, math got a reliable language for “and/or,” “all/some,” relations, functions, and counting arguments. Sets became the stage where discrete math performs its best scenes.",
      "title": "Why sets still matter now"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture a 1950s computer room: humming cabinets, punch cards in shoeboxes. Data wasn’t “stored” so much as stacked—like recipes scattered across a kitchen with no labels.",
      "title": "When data was a messy pantry"
    },
    {
      "text": "Need one customer record? You’d run a whole batch job and wait. Finding a single fact felt like flipping every page in a phone book… by flashlight… in the rain.",
      "title": "The agony of “find me one thing”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Early systems kept info in flat files—long lists on tape. But tape is like a cassette: great for play-through, terrible for skipping to track 37.",
      "title": "Life on tapes and flat files"
    },
    {
      "text": "As businesses grew, so did the knots: duplicate data, mismatched updates, missing versions. Changing one form meant rewriting half the programs—like moving a wall and rebuilding the whole house.",
      "title": "The “change one thing, break ten” trap"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came a bold idea: separate data from the programs that use it. Let many apps share one trusted store—like a public library instead of everyone hoarding photocopies.",
      "title": "A new promise: shared, central truth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Researchers started treating data like something you could model: records, links, rules. Instead of piles of papers, you’d have a map of a city—streets connecting places on purpose.",
      "title": "Drawing maps, not piling papers"
    },
    {
      "text": "The big turning point: the relational model. Store facts in tables and ask questions with a clean language, without telling the computer every step—like ordering from a menu instead of cooking blind.",
      "title": "Tables and questions, not instructions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Databases became the backstage crew of modern life: banking, playlists, hospital charts, online shopping. When they’re good, everything feels instant; when they fail, the world stutters.",
      "title": "Why databases still run the show"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture Paris in the mid-1800s: galleries like velvet-lined courts. Paintings were polished like marble—myth, history, perfect skin, perfect light. If your brushstroke showed, it was like showing up to a ball in muddy boots.",
      "title": "When art had to be “perfect”"
    },
    {
      "text": "The gatekeeper was the Salon, a giant official show. Get in and you’re somebody; get rejected and you’re invisible. Artists painted to please judges—like cooking for one picky critic instead of real hungry people.",
      "title": "The Salon: art’s bouncer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then modern life started sprinting. Trains, cafés, busy streets, smoke, glittering river light—moments that vanished in a blink. The old studio style felt like trying to pin a butterfly with boxing gloves.",
      "title": "A world moving too fast"
    },
    {
      "text": "New tools helped artists chase the chase. Paint came in portable tubes, so you could paint outdoors. Suddenly the “studio” could be a riverbank, a boulevard, a windy field—where light changes every minute.",
      "title": "Paint breaks out of the studio"
    },
    {
      "text": "Some painters began chasing the *first* impression: the quick hit of color your eye grabs before your brain tidies it up. Shadows weren’t black—they were blue, violet, green. The canvas became a weather report.",
      "title": "Seeing like an eye, not a camera"
    },
    {
      "text": "Their brushwork stayed visible—little dabs and strokes, like notes in a fast jazz solo. Up close it looked messy; from a few steps back, it snapped into life. Your eyes did part of the mixing.",
      "title": "Brushstrokes you could feel"
    },
    {
      "text": "They kept getting turned away, so they staged their own exhibition in 1874. A critic mocked one painting’s title—“Impression, Sunrise”—and tossed out “Impressionists” like an insult. The name stuck like glue.",
      "title": "Rejected… so they made their own show"
    },
    {
      "text": "What changed wasn’t just style—it was permission. Permission to paint ordinary people, ordinary places, and fleeting light. Art didn’t have to be a statue; it could be a moment you almost miss.",
      "title": "A new rule: the moment matters"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, Impressionism shapes how we read images—photos, films, even Instagram sunsets. It trained us to love the everyday shimmer of life, and to trust that a “quick glance” can tell a deeper truth.",
      "title": "Why we still see through their eyes"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine tentar entender uma cidade só olhando da janela. Por séculos, foi assim: explicavam a vida social com religião, tradição e “sempre foi desse jeito”. Funcionava… até o mundo mudar rápido demais.",
      "title": "Quando “sempre foi assim” bastava"
    },
    {
      "text": "A Europa virou um canteiro de obras: fábricas, fumaça, gente chegando às cidades, jornadas longas. Como um time que troca de técnico no meio do jogo, as regras sociais mudaram sem aviso — e a confusão veio junto.",
      "title": "A vida acelera: cidades e fábricas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Riqueza de um lado, miséria do outro. Greves, revoltas, medo e esperança. Era como tentar cozinhar com a receita antiga num fogão novo: as mesmas ideias já não davam conta de explicar pobreza, crime, trabalho e poder.",
      "title": "O choque: desigualdade e conflitos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Filósofos opinavam, políticos prometiam, moralistas julgavam. Mas faltava um mapa confiável. Cada um puxava para um lado — como torcedores discutindo o jogo sem ver o replay. Nasceu a pergunta: dá pra estudar a sociedade com método?",
      "title": "Palpites não resolvem o caos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com as ciências naturais brilhando, surgiu a ambição: se dá para medir estrelas e micróbios, por que não observar padrões de vida em grupo? A ideia era trocar achismo por investigação: comparar, registrar, buscar causas.",
      "title": "A virada: olhar científico"
    },
    {
      "text": "Assim aparece a Sociologia: um jeito de enxergar o “invisível” do cotidiano — normas, instituições, classes, cultura. Como colocar óculos novos: de repente, o que parecia pessoal revela peças de um quebra-cabeça social maior.",
      "title": "Nasce a Sociologia"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hoje, redes sociais, trabalho por app, polarização, violência, movimentos por direitos. A Sociologia importa porque ajuda a separar caso isolado de tendência, culpa individual de estrutura — e a entender como a vida em grupo nos molda.",
      "title": "Por que isso importa agora"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture sorting a messy closet. You don’t tackle “everything” at once—you pick one shelf, then one box, then one pile. Big problems become bearable when you can keep carving them into smaller copies of themselves.",
      "title": "When “too big” is the enemy"
    },
    {
      "text": "Early programs often felt like rigid assembly lines: do step 1, then 2, then 3. Great for simple tasks, but awkward for things shaped like family trees, nested folders, or “puzzles inside puzzles.”",
      "title": "Straight lines met twisty problems"
    },
    {
      "text": "People tried to manage the mess with clever loops and extra bookkeeping—sticky notes everywhere: counters, stacks, special cases. It worked, but the code could read like a cookbook written in panic.",
      "title": "Loops with too many sticky notes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came a calmer idea: what if a function could ask a smaller version of itself for help? Like a set of Russian nesting dolls—open one, and inside is the same shape, just smaller.",
      "title": "The nesting-doll insight"
    },
    {
      "text": "Of course, every good story needs an exit. Recursion only works if there’s a “stop sign”—a simplest case you can solve immediately. No stop sign, and you’re stuck in an infinite hallway of doors.",
      "title": "The all-important stop sign"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once that clicked, problems like traversing trees, exploring mazes, and breaking apart lists suddenly had a natural script. The solution matched the shape of the problem, like a key cut to the lock.",
      "title": "Code that mirrors the problem"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, recursion is a mental superpower: it trains you to think in patterns, not just steps. Even when you use loops later, that recursive viewpoint helps you see the hidden structure in complex tasks.",
      "title": "Why it still matters now"
    }
  ]
}
